[hr]

[size=16pt][b][color=#ffaa00]👤 Founder & Lead Architect[/color][/b][/size]

[b]Background:[/b] A visionary technologist with roots in Danish academic excellence. After studying [b]Information Technology and Business Economics at Copenhagen Business School (CBS)[/b] in Frederiksberg for three years, I made a strategic decision: leave academia and pursue hands-on entrepreneurship—choosing the startup battlefield over the lecture hall.

[quote][i]"I didn't drop out of business school—I graduated to the startup battlefield."[/i][/quote]

[b]🔧 Two Decades of Code (20 years):[/b]
From distributed systems to consensus protocols, I've built production infrastructure since before "blockchain" became mainstream. Every line of code reflects battle-tested engineering discipline.

[b]⚛️ Quantum Physics Research (20 years):[/b]
Parallel to programming, 20 years of dedicated quantum physics study uniquely positioned me to bridge theoretical quantum mechanics with practical cryptographic implementations. This rare combination drives Q-NarwhalKnight's post-quantum security architecture.

[b]🔐 Cypherpunk to the Bone:[/b]
Privacy is a fundamental right. Cryptography is the tool to protect it. This isn't ideology—it's embedded in every design decision, from Tor integration to quantum-resistant signatures.

[b]💰 Decentralization Advocate:[/b]
Q-NarwhalKnight isn't just another blockchain—it's a manifestation of the belief that individuals should control their own money, free from centralized intermediaries and surveillance.

[b]📱 Mobile-First Vision:[/b]
Smartphone apps are the gateway to mainstream adoption. Our quantum wallet's intuitive interface proves that cutting-edge cryptography doesn't require a PhD to use.

[hr]

[size=16pt][b][color=#ffaa00]🌟 Heroes & Inspirations[/color][/b][/size]

[size=14pt][b]Zooko Wilcox (Zcash)[/b][/size] [color=#00ff00]★ MY HERO ★[/color]

Zooko demonstrated that privacy and regulatory compliance can coexist, that cypherpunk ideals can scale to production blockchains, and that cutting-edge cryptography belongs in real-world financial systems. Zcash's success proved privacy-focused blockchain is viable—Q-NarwhalKnight extends that vision into the post-quantum era.

[size=14pt][b]Eli Ben-Sasson (StarkWare, Tel Aviv)[/b][/size]

The inventor of [b]zk-STARKs[/b] ignited my passion for zero-knowledge cryptography and cryptographic scalability. His groundbreaking work at Technion (Tel Aviv) and later StarkWare showed how academic cryptographic breakthroughs transform into production systems serving millions. The zk-STARK invention—eliminating trusted setups from zero-knowledge proofs—was a paradigm shift.

[size=14pt][b]Satoshi Nakamoto[/b][/size]

The monk who walked away. Satoshi chose anonymity, purity of vision, and minimal infrastructure. I respect that path deeply—but I'm choosing a different route.

[b]What They Taught Me:[/b]
[list]
[*][b]From Zooko:[/b] Privacy is non-negotiable, but implementation must be practical
[*][b]From Eli:[/b] Academic rigor and production systems aren't contradictory
[*][b]From Satoshi:[/b] Decentralized money works—now bring it to the world
[/list]

[quote][b]Q-NarwhalKnight = Zooko's privacy + Eli's cryptography + Satoshi's vision + Post-quantum security[/b][/quote]

