[size=14pt][b][color=#ff6600]Why The Merchant's Path?[/color][/b][/size]

Satoshi proved decentralized money works. But for mainstream adoption, we need [b]infrastructure—not isolation[/b].

[b][color=#ff0000]Quillon Bank is NOT a bridge that can be hacked.[/color][/b]

It's a [b]non-custodial, cryptographically-governed banking layer[/b] built directly on Q-NarwhalKnight:

[list]
[*][b]⚛️ Post-quantum security[/b] (blockchain layer)
[*][b]👤 Traditional banking UX[/b] (familiar interfaces)
[*][b]🔐 Cryptographic access control[/b] (AEGIS-QL - you control your keys)
[*][b]🔄 Atomic swaps[/b] for cross-chain transfers (NO bridge vulnerabilities)
[*][b]🚫 Zero custodial risk[/b] (fully non-custodial)
[*][b]🌐 True decentralization[/b] (no central authority)
[/list]

[quote][size=12pt][b][color=#00ff00]"Bridges get hacked. Atomic swaps are trustless. Quillon Bank uses cryptography, not trust."[/color][/b][/size][/quote]

Satoshi walked the monk's path and changed the world. I'm walking the merchant's path to bring that world to everyone—[b]without compromising security through bridges or custodians[/b].

